@node "Introduction" "SpIntroduction"
@next "Main"
@prev "Main"
SPin is yet another attempt at implementing file_id.diz to MAXs (although I
hope you consider it a successful one)


Basically SPin is a total re-write of MAXs own file base. It's completely
compatible with MAXs built in base. It reads BBS:MaxsBBS.config for the
following
                    Section Access Levels
                    Section Attributes (Aliases, Links etc.)
                    New Files Public flag
                    Files Path
                    Optional Files Path
                    Text Path (for ListFilesMenu.text)
                    Userfiles path (for Alias cross reference)

It also accesses, and updates the  File.data and  File.index, thus allowing
you to use MAXs built in File Editor to edit/delete/make_public/lock files.

Now access the User.Index to cross reference an entered Alias with any user
currently in the user base.  I mention this only because you may see it acces
user.index in snoopdos and go "ah, a back door".. well it ain't, if you know
enough about MAXs you'll know that access levels and all other info's
relating to the user are stored in User.DATA


It's main feature is file_id.diz, however theres various little extras I cant
be bothered listing  :)    You'll see as you go along, you'll be surprised,
but impressed :)

Ah yeah, and it now also has byte ratios.  :) 


I wont bother telling you what I think about it, coz I'm biased ;) Check it
out dude, the worst you can do is waste 1 minute installing it and since the
installer makes a backup of your current config before updating it, well it's
easy to de-install.


You've probably noticed how crap these docs are.  Read Changes.Readme to find
out features and stuff coz I can't be bothered writing it all out in a
different format.


Now jump back to the @{"Main" link "Main" 0} part of this guide and read the rest.
                                          
@endnode

@node "Installation" "SpIntallation (God it's simple!)"
@next "Main"
@prev "Main"
Installation is very simple, all you do is run the installer script. It's
called SpInstall. You MUST be in the same dir as SpInstall when you execute
it.

In tests, I've timed the installer script to install the COMPLETE system
within 10 seconds!

SpInstall will add the assign to your user-startup as well as creating dirs
and copying/creating any necessary files. You must have a Doors: Assign set-up
for the installer script, although SPin itself does not need this assign. It
will also execute a small prog that updates your MAXs text lines
(MAXsBBS.config) to suit SPin.

SpInstall will prompt you, asking you if you already have an external file
base, if not it'll execute yet another small prog that will update all the
menu functions in your MAXsBBS.Config.

Note: A backup of your old MAXsBBS.config is made called
"BBS:MAXsBBS.config.B4SPin"

Once all is completed load SPin:Config/SPin.Config into a text editor and edit
as you please, it's documented anyway, so I dont need to explain it's
functions here.

Take note that if you already have a Download door installed, most notably a
Goodbye After Transfer door, then you'll have to install SPinDown manually
SPin has a goodbye after transfer feature built in anyhows.


IMPORTANT

When adding sections, adjusting section attributes etc. You MUST SAVE your
config, if you run a multinode system and have several configs, you must have
a copy called  BBS:MAXsBBS.Config otherwise SPin will refuse to work.



If you DO currently have an external file base set up, and have executed the
installer before reading this. Then do the following

De-Install your external file base manually, RE-Install MAXs OLD file base
(menu functions List / Upload / Download / Edit-Marked-Files /
UnMark-All-Files) then run

InstallerUtils/MenuUpdate.exe




Here's the parameters for the doors.

SPinList XYZ              Where XYZ = section number, X, XY, or XYZ is Ok.


SPinUp XY "upload path"   XY = section The upload path must be in quotes.
SPinUp CHECK              This goes in the introdoor.text, checks for
                          files uploaded, then carrier lost before a
                          diz was extracted/entered. Also informs user if
                          they have files on their tag list.

SPinDown                  No Parameters.


EditMarked                No Parameters.


UnMarkAll                 No Parameters.


SPinLogoff                No Parameters.  (replaces Logoff function)


The logoff door is for informing the user they still have flagged files.
SPinLogoff will allow them to save/del the taglist, or abort logoff.


Jump back to @{"Main" link "Main" 0}                                    
@endnode

@node "Customisation" "Customisation"
SPin isn't as customisable as you may like to be, you can edit basic things,
like the colour of file lists, mem usage for keyword searches and elimanate
an annoying "feature of MAXs"

With MAXs a user can download U x R + R files where

U = No of Uploads and

R = Ratio


In SPin:Configs/SPin.Config theres a line which says

Free_Downloads = 3

To disable the MAXs free download feature you can make the 3 into a 0. Also
note that this number can not exceed R or MAXs will screw up.


Max_Hunt_Buffer = 15000

means that only 15000 bytes will be used when doing a keyword search, note
that if you set this higher than the size of SPin:DIz/SPeedSEarch.DIzs it'll
only allocate the file's size. The bigger the buffer the faster it will do
the scan.

Also try to keep this file defrag'd. Do this by using the following command
lines about every month or so

copy speedsearch.dizs defragged.dizs

delete speedsearch.dizs

rename defragged.dizs speedsearch.dizs


----------------Update---------------------------------------

Now has an extra 2 lines in config, they're self explanitory.

---------------Yet another update----------------------------

Erm, yeah, it has yet another 2 extra lines in the config, so read "Byte
Ratios" and you'll see what they are.
-------------------------------------------------------------

To find out how to edit the colour of file lists click that ==> @{"Colour" link "Colour" 0}
Otherwise, click that ==> @{"Main" link "Main" 0}                                         
@endnode

@node "Colour" "Colourful things are very colourful and stuff."
Now a function a few sysops showed me with their external file base was the
colour of file lists. Their colour editor was in the form of a door, I decided
to go for the easiest method and used MAXs text lines. Lazy? Or sensible?


Line (MAXs text line)

320   Before uploaders name, end with colour of the uploaders name.

321   After uploaders name

322   Color of file descriptions

323   Color of division Line

324   Color of "bytes xxxx"

325   Color of upload date/time


Example1: You want it to say "Screwed up by UPLOADER, kewl, huh?" and you want
the "Screwed up by", ", kewl, huh?" in light green and the uploaders name in
cyan, then line 320 and 321 would be as follows

321:  ^[[1;32mScrewed up by ^[[0;36m

322:  ^[[1;32m , kewl, huh?

Note that if you do not customise the text functions the defaults are
standard. The ONLY 2 Lines that are NECESSARY are lines 320 and 321 and the
only real part that makes any difference is the color at the end of line 320.
You needn't worry too much tho coz the installer puts line 320 and 321 in
automatically!

Example2: You want the file descriptions to be dark red in color. Well all you
do is put this into line 322.

322:  ^[[0;31m

and it's that simple B-)

Back to @{"Main" link "Main" 0}                           
@endnode

@node "Bugs" "Bugs, call Rentokil NOW!"
I've only really found a couple of problems with SPin, the main one being
memory usage, the List door requires the full File.data, thus meaning the
larger your file base the more mem required. Currently I run on a basic A1200
no fast ram, (upgrading soon tho :-) ) and I can get by with up to around 1800
files online.  Future updates will use less mem, though they may be slower.
Note, quick update here, I forgot to mention that it'll allocate "any" mem,
thus allowing for VMem.


Lines per screen. This ones a bit weird. Other file bases haven't really
approached the problem. You see because generally MAXs uses cursor flagging of
files, which is nice, but does cause problems. The real problem is that MAXs
is limited to 26 lines per screen, thus meaning that if the user attempts to
move the cursor further up than this, they will get hit with a load of Ansi
positioning codes. There is no practical way round this so SPin takes, what I
think is, the best approach. Here's the conditions.

1) A user has <=26 lines per screen set. No problems, file lists look
   perfect.

2) A user has 27-30 lines per screen. SPin will divide the page by inserting
blank lines (faking the top of the screen). The local sysop will think it
looks horrible, but all the user sees is a new page of files, without a trace
of the last page.

3) A user has 31+ lines per screen set. Cursor flagging disabled and file
names must be entered manually.


Pause Flag. SPinList has to disable the Pause After Screen Full flag because
the flag sometimes screws up the display. It will set it again afterwards.
However it's impossible to set the flag if the user loses carrier during a
file list.  SPinUp forces it back on next time they login. This is why SPinUp
has to be in the IntroDoor.text and not the MainDoor.text. If it where in the
MainDoor.text and the flag was off. Long messages (mail) would fly past
without them getting a chance to read them.


Killing files does not kill it's file_id.diz (keep in contact with my board
and you'll get a util that'll clean up all the del'd file's Id's.


Batch downloads are simulated with multiple single download. This is yet
another problem with MAXs. Other file bases have the same. The commercial
version will use an XPR thus, eliminating this prob.


I think that covers all the nuances and minor probs. Contact me if you find
any more. Jump back to @{"Main" link "Main" 0}
             
@endnode

