@node "Multinodes" "Multi-Nodes and Local Nodes"


SPin works with no problems on a multinode system. Although theres ARE a few
things I must point out.

Apart from creating SPin:Node2/  you'll have to change all the scripts.

You may notice that all the scripts have strings like "$UploadedFile1" change
all these strings to "$UploadedFile2" "$UploadPath2" etc.

IMPORTANT

Local uploads will be written to SPin:Node0/

To do a local upload, copy the files to SPin:Node0/ then go to upload the way
a user would.

Back to @{"Main" link "Main" 0}                       
@endnode

@node "ByteRatios" "Byte Ratios and other things that bite you."
Byte ratios are ultra complex to use and will cause you no end of grief and
you'll have to take out a will before considering setting them up coz it's all
so difficult and annyoing and you'll hate doing it and probably die of old age
in the process.

So now that I've covered every other file base for MAXs, here's how easy it is
with SPin :)

Byte ratios in SPin very simple to set up.  There IS a loss however. Some
password doors and quick login doors use the User Comment String.

Well I've decided to use it too.  Mainly because I didnt want to code a door
that did very little and could be done by much simpler means. Also it means
less configs for you to pull your hair out over. Ah yeah and it means you can
edit ratios with an online edit too! :)

The format for these byte ratios is simple.

Ratio=4  Uploaded=55232  Downloaded=43535

The installer will add the following line to your config

Force_Byte_Ratio = 0

When set to 0 the user's ratio type is "Files Only" and their user comment
string won't be touched.  By setting this number to, say, 4, it'll give all
user's who DON'T HAVE A BYTE RATIO a ratio of 4, if the user HAS a ratio set
at, say, 6, it wont touch it.

Another line in the config is

Free_Bytes = 100000

This is just like the "Free_Downloads" line except for bytes.  I should have
made the "Free_Downloads" line say "Free_Files" 'cept I didn't so there!


How byte size is handled.

The size of the file is read in at the start of the file scan Once all the
stripping and adding is completed, it's file size is read again It will put
the new file size as the size of the file online. BUT will only credit the
user with the LOWEST reading.

Example 1:
   User uploads "Whatever.Nfo"

   Initial Size = 250k (200k of banners of course!)

   Strips it down to 50k

   Adds your 10k Banners

   New file size = 60k

   Online Size = 60k

   User creditted with 60k


Example 2:
    User uploads "Coolness.Lha"

    Initial Size 170k

    Strip 6k of addy's

    Adds your 17k Jpg

    New file size = 181k

    Online size = 181k

    User creditted with 170k   <<<  INITIAL file size was SMALLER!





Erm, thats about it for byte ratios, didn't I say it was simple?


Now click @{"THIS" link "Main" 0} thingy and go back to main coz there's nufin else to read in
this bit...


@endnode

